# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: proof-theory-logic
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The **cut-elimination theorem** (or **Gentzen's *Hauptsatz***) is the central result establishing the significance of the sequent calculus.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] It was originally proved by Gerhard Gentzen in part I of his landmark 1935 paper "Investigations in Logical Deduction" for the systems LJ and LK formalising intuitionistic and classical logic respectively.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The cut-elimination theorem states that any sequent that possesses a proof in the sequent calculus making use of the **cut rule** also possesses a **cut-free proof**, that is, a proof that does not make use of the cut rule.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The natural deduction version of cut-elimination, known as the *normalization theorem*, was first proved for a variety of logics by Dag Prawitz in 1965 (a similar but less general proof was given the same year by Andrès Raggio).
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] There are many different possible sequent calculuses for many logics, and consequently there are many different cut-elimination theorems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Indeed, cut-elimination is such an important genre of theorems in logic, that logicians speak of "this logic has cut-elimination" as a way to say that this logic has a desirable property.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Conversely, if a formalism or a logic does not have cut-elimination, that is usually considered a point against it, and would motivate research into finding a new formalism, or a modification of the logic, such that cut-elimination is true, or an analog of cut-elimination is true.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The LHS may have arbitrarily many or few formulae; when the LHS is empty, the RHS is a tautology.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] However, the sequent calculus is a fairly expressive framework, and there have been sequent calculi for intuitionistic logic proposed that allow many formulae in the RHS.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] From Jean-Yves Girard's logic LC it is easy to obtain a rather natural formalisation of classical logic where the RHS contains at most one formula; it is the interplay of the logical and structural rules that is the key here.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] That is, it "cuts" the occurrences of the formula A out of the inferential relation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The cut-elimination theorem states that (for a given system) any sequent provable using the rule Cut can be proved without use of this rule.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] If we think of B as a theorem, then cut-elimination in this case simply says that a lemma A used to prove this theorem can be inlined.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Whenever the theorem's proof mentions lemma A , we can substitute the occurrences for the proof of A .
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Consequently, the cut rule is admissible.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] To avoid confusion, note that there are two meanings of "proof" here.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] There is the "proof" as a sequent calculus proof-tree.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] This proof is a mathematical object, and it is an object studied by proof theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] There is also the "proof" as a mathematical argument that is written normally in natural language by mathematicians.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The cut-elimination theorem is a theorem about proof-trees.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] To "prove the cut-elimination theorem" means to write down a proof-argument for the cut-elimination theorem.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] A proof of a cut-elimination theorem generally goes as follows.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Lists out all the inference rules of a sequent calculus.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] A proof tree is a tree where each node is an application of an inference rule.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] We regard the proof trees as expressions in an abstract language, and then describe rewriting rules.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Now one simply need to prove that the system of rewriting rules is terminating.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] That is, any sequence of rewriting can only last finitely many steps.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] In other words, one need to show that the rewriting system is well-founded.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] To prove that the system is terminating, one usually designs an ordinal numbering system.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] For each proof tree T , define a corresponding ordinal number $o(T)$ , then shows that each rewriting step $T\implies T'$ has $o(T)>o(T')$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Then, since the ordinals are well-founded, the rewriting system is too.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] This line of thought also leads to ordinal analysis.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] That is, in order to prove the system is terminating, one need to assume that $\sup _{T{\text{ is a proof tree}}}o(T)$ is well-ordered.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] For example, in the case of Gentzen's original proof, he showed that $\sup _{T{\text{ is a proof tree}}}o(T)=\epsilon _{0}$ the 0th epsilon number.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Conversely, Peano arithmetic can prove any ordinal lower than $\epsilon _{0}$ is well-founded, but not $\epsilon _{0}$ itself.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Thus the common saying "the consistency of Peano arithmetic is equivalent to the well-foundedness of $\epsilon _{0}$ ".
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Consider the typical sequent calculus for propositional LK.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] We require sequents to be finite multisets, so that we can ignore the bureaucratic annoyance of the exchange rule.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The cut rule is ${\frac {\Gamma \vdash \Delta ,A\qquad A,\Pi \vdash \Lambda }{\Gamma ,\Pi \vdash \Delta ,\Lambda }}\operatorname {Cut} .$ We give 5 illustrative examples.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Note that we use "multiplicative" versions of the inference rules of conjunction and disjunction, since they are more convenient for eliminating cuts.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] It would bubble upwards until it meets "resistance" in the form of principal cuts.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Identity axiom, principal rule ${\frac {{\overline {A\vdash A}}^{\operatorname {Id} }\qquad A,\Pi \vdash \Lambda }{A,\Pi \vdash \Lambda }}\operatorname {Cut} \quad \implies \quad A,\Pi \vdash \Lambda .$ This is how some cuts may eventually disappear, by canceling out a leaf of the proof tree.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The cut formula A is introduced by weakening in the right premiss, so that occurrence of A is unused.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The left premiss is discarded, and the original endsequent is recovered from $\Pi \vdash \Lambda$ by weakening.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The contraction in the right premiss has identified two occurrences of the cut formula A .
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The rewrite first cuts against one occurrence of A , then cuts against the other occurrence of A .
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The final contractions identify the duplicated copies of $\Gamma$ and $\Delta$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Most of the rewriting rules straightforwardly make progress on eliminating the cuts, either by pushing a cut closer to the leafs, or by destroying a cut at the price of possibly making the tree longer.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The only exception is the case of contraction, principal rule.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] In this case, two cuts appeared in the place of one, and the tree increased massively in size.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] This is still a terminating rewriting rule, but proving this requires care.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Essentially due to the contraction principle rule, cut-elimination increases the size of proof superexponentially.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] By the Curry–Howard correspondence, cut-elimination corresponds to beta-reduction of simply typed lambda terms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Rewriting corresponds to beta-reduction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Rewriting across a contraction rule corresponds to beta-reduction of form $(\lambda fx.f(fx))t$ , and beta-reduction of $\underbrace {(\lambda fx.f(fx))\cdots (\lambda fx.f(fx))} _{n{\text{ times}}}$ may take $^{n}2$ time, where the notation is tetration.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Quantifier rules have analogous principal reductions, with the usual proviso that eigenvariables are always renamed before rewriting, to avoid accidentally capture.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] For example, a principal cut between $\forall _{R}$ and $\forall _{L}$ is reduced by substituting the term used in the left rule into the eigenvariable proof from the right rule, then cutting on the resulting instance.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Thus the rewriting step preserves the endsequent while replacing a cut on $\forall x\,A(x)$ by a cut on an instance $A(t)$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] For systems formulated in the sequent calculus, analytic proofs are those proofs that do not use Cut.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Typically such a proof will be longer, of course, and not necessarily trivially so.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] In his essay "Don't Eliminate Cut!" George Boolos demonstrated that there was a derivation that could be completed in a page using cut, but whose analytic proof could not be completed in the lifespan of the universe.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] Cut elimination is one of the most powerful tools for proving interpolation theorems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] The possibility of carrying out proof search based on resolution, the essential insight leading to the Prolog programming language, depends upon the admissibility of Cut in the appropriate system.
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] For proof systems based on higher-order typed lambda calculus through a Curry–Howard isomorphism, cut elimination algorithms correspond to the strong normalization property (every proof term reduces in a finite number of steps into a normal form).
[src:proof-theory-logic/cut-elimination-theorem] An analogous result of strong normalisation for various calculi of Natural Deduction was first proved by Dag Prawitz.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Gentzen's theorem is concerned with first-order arithmetic: the theory of the natural numbers, including their addition and multiplication, axiomatized by the first-order Peano axioms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] This is a "first-order" theory: the quantifiers extend over natural numbers, but not over sets or functions of natural numbers.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] The theory is strong enough to describe recursively defined integer functions such as exponentiation, factorials or the Fibonacci sequence.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Gentzen showed that the consistency of the first-order Peano axioms is provable over the base theory of primitive recursive arithmetic with the additional principle of quantifier-free transfinite induction up to the ordinal ε0.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Primitive recursive arithmetic is a much simplified form of arithmetic that is rather uncontroversial.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] The additional principle means, informally, that there is a well-ordering on the set of finite rooted trees.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] It is a countable ordinal much smaller than large countable ordinals.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] To express ordinals in the language of arithmetic, an ordinal notation is needed, i.e. a way to assign natural numbers to ordinals less than ε0.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] This can be done in various ways, one example provided by Cantor's normal form theorem.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Gentzen's proof is based on the following assumption: for any quantifier-free formula A(x), if there is an ordinal *a*< ε0 for which A(a) is false, then there is a least such ordinal.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Gentzen defines a notion of "reduction procedure" for proofs in Peano arithmetic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] For a given proof, such a procedure produces a tree of proofs, with the given one serving as the root of the tree, and the other proofs being, in a sense, "simpler" than the given one.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] This increasing simplicity is formalized by attaching an ordinal < ε0 to every proof, and showing that, as one moves down the tree, these ordinals get smaller with every step.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] He then shows that if there were a proof of a contradiction, the reduction procedure would result in an infinite strictly descending sequence of ordinals smaller than ε0 produced by a primitive recursive operation on proofs corresponding to a quantifier-free formula.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Gentzen's proof highlights one commonly missed aspect of Gödel's second incompleteness theorem.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] It is sometimes claimed that the consistency of a theory can only be proved in a stronger theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Gentzen's theory obtained by adding quantifier-free transfinite induction to primitive recursive arithmetic proves the consistency of first-order Peano arithmetic (PA) but does not contain PA.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] For example, it does not prove ordinary mathematical induction for all formulae, whereas PA does (since all instances of induction are axioms of PA).
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Gentzen's theory is not contained in PA, either, however, since it can prove a number-theoretical fact—the consistency of PA—that PA cannot.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Therefore, the two theories are, in one sense, incomparable.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] That said, there are other, finer ways to compare the strength of theories, the most important of which is defined in terms of the notion of interpretability.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] It can be shown that, if one theory T is interpretable in another B, then T is consistent if B is.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] (Indeed, this is a large point of the notion of interpretability.) And, assuming that T is not extremely weak, T itself will be able to prove this very conditional: If B is consistent, then so is T.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Hence, T cannot prove that B is consistent, by the second incompleteness theorem, whereas B may well be able to prove that T is consistent.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] This is what motivates the idea of using interpretability to compare theories, i.e., the thought that, if B interprets T, then B is at least as strong (in the sense of 'consistency strength') as T is.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] A strong form of the second incompleteness theorem, proved by Pavel Pudlák, who was building on earlier work by Solomon Feferman, states that no consistent theory T that contains Robinson arithmetic, Q, can interpret Q plus Con(T), the statement that T is consistent.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] By contrast, Q+Con(T) *does* interpret T, by a strong form of the arithmetized completeness theorem.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] So Q+Con(T) is always stronger (in one good sense) than T is.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] But Gentzen's theory trivially interprets Q+Con(PA), since it contains Q and proves Con(PA), and so Gentzen's theory interprets PA.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] But, by Pudlák's result, PA *cannot* interpret Gentzen's theory, since Gentzen's theory (as just said) interprets Q+Con(PA), and interpretability is transitive.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] That is: If PA did interpret Gentzen's theory, then it would also interpret Q+Con(PA) and so would be inconsistent, by Pudlák's result.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] So, in the sense of consistency strength, as characterized by interpretability, Gentzen's theory is stronger than Peano arithmetic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Hermann Weyl made the following comment in 1946 regarding the significance of Gentzen's consistency result following the devastating impact of Gödel's 1931 incompleteness result on Hilbert's plan to prove the consistency of mathematics.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] It is likely that all mathematicians ultimately would have accepted Hilbert's approach had he been able to carry it out successfully.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] The first steps were inspiring and promising.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] But then Gödel dealt it a terrific blow (1931), from which it has not yet recovered.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Gödel enumerated the symbols, formulas, and sequences of formulas in Hilbert's formalism in a certain way, and thus transformed the assertion of consistency into an arithmetic proposition.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] He could show that this proposition can neither be proved nor disproved within the formalism.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] 479) made the following comment in 1952 on the significance of Gentzen's result, particularly in the context of the formalist program which was initiated by Hilbert.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] It thus became apparent that the 'finite Standpunkt' is not the only alternative to classical ways of reasoning and is not necessarily implied by the idea of proof theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] An enlarging of the methods of proof theory was therefore suggested: instead of a reduction to finitist methods of reasoning, it was required only that the arguments be of a constructive character, allowing us to deal with more general forms of inference.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Gentzen's first version of his consistency proof was not published during his lifetime because Paul Bernays had objected to a method implicitly used in the proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] The modified proof, described above, was published in 1936 in the *Annals*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Gentzen went on to publish two more consistency proofs, one in 1938 and one in 1943.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] All of these are contained in (Gentzen & Szabo 1969).
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Kurt Gödel reinterpreted Gentzen's 1936 proof in a lecture in 1938 in what came to be known as the no-counterexample interpretation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Both the original proof and the reformulation can be understood in game-theoretic terms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] In 1940 Wilhelm Ackermann published another consistency proof for Peano arithmetic, also using the ordinal ε0.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Another proof of consistency of Arithmetic was published by I.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Gentzen's proof is the first example of what is called proof-theoretic ordinal analysis.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] In ordinal analysis one gauges the strength of theories by measuring how large the (constructive) ordinals are that can be proven to be well-ordered, or equivalently for how large a (constructive) ordinal can transfinite induction be proven.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] A constructive ordinal is the order type of a recursive well-ordering of natural numbers.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] In this language, Gentzen's work establishes that the proof-theoretic ordinal of first-order Peano arithmetic is ε0.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Laurence Kirby and Jeff Paris proved in 1982 that Goodstein's theorem cannot be proven in Peano arithmetic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/gentzen-s-consistency-proof] Their proof was based on Gentzen's theorem.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In logic and proof theory, **natural deduction** is a kind of proof calculus in which logical reasoning is expressed by inference rules closely related to the "natural" way of reasoning.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This contrasts with Hilbert-style systems, which instead use axioms as much as possible to express the logical laws of deductive reasoning.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Natural deduction grew out of a context of dissatisfaction with the axiomatizations of deductive reasoning common to the systems of Hilbert, Frege, and Russell (see, e.g., Hilbert system).
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Such axiomatizations were most famously used by Russell and Whitehead in their mathematical treatise *Principia Mathematica*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] His proposals led to different notations such as Fitch notation or Suppes' method, for which Lemmon gave a variant now known as Suppes–Lemmon notation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Natural deduction in its modern form was independently proposed by the German mathematician Gerhard Gentzen in 1933, in a dissertation delivered to the faculty of mathematical sciences of the University of Göttingen.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Gentzen was motivated by a desire to establish the consistency of number theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] He was unable to prove the main result required for the consistency result, the cut elimination theorem—the Hauptsatz—directly for natural deduction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] For this reason he introduced his alternative system, the sequent calculus, for which he proved the Hauptsatz both for classical and intuitionistic logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In a series of seminars in 1961 and 1962 Prawitz gave a comprehensive summary of natural deduction calculi, and transported much of Gentzen's work with sequent calculi into the natural deduction framework.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] His 1965 monograph *Natural deduction: a proof-theoretical study* was to become a reference work on natural deduction, and included applications for modal and second-order logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In natural deduction, a proposition is deduced from a collection of premises by applying inference rules repeatedly.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The system presented in this article is a minor variation of Gentzen's or Prawitz's formulation, but with a closer adherence to Martin-Löf's description of logical judgments and connectives.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Natural deduction has had a large variety of notation styles, which can make it difficult to recognize a proof for a reader not familiar with one of them.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] To help with this situation, this article has a § Notation section explaining how to read all the notation that it will actually use.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This section just explains the historical evolution of notation styles, most of which cannot be shown because there are no illustrations available under a public copyright license – the reader is pointed to the SEP and IEP for pictures.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Here is a table with the most common notational variants for logical connectives.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Gentzen, who invented natural deduction, had his own notation style for arguments.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This will be exemplified by a simple argument below.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Let's say we have a simple example argument in propositional logic, such as, "if it's raining then it's cloudly; it is raining; therefore it's cloudy".
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The premises are shown above a line, called the **inference line**, separated by a **comma**, which indicates *combination* of premises.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The conclusion is written below the inference line.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The inference line represents *syntactic consequence*, sometimes called *deductive consequence*, which is also symbolized with ⊢.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] So the above can also be written in one line as $P\to Q,P\vdash Q$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Syntactic consequence is contrasted with *semantic consequence*, which is symbolized with ⊧.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In this case, the conclusion follows *syntactically* because natural deduction is a syntactic proof system, which assumes inference rules as primitives.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Gentzen's style will be used in much of this article.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Gentzen's discharging annotations used to internalise hypothetical judgments can be avoided by representing proofs as a tree of sequents *Γ* ⊢ *A* instead of a tree of judgments that *A* (is true).
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Many textbooks use Suppes–Lemmon notation, so this article will also give that – although as of now, this is only included for propositional logic, and the rest of the coverage is given only in Gentzen style.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] A **proof**, laid out in accordance with the Suppes–Lemmon notation style, is a sequence of lines containing sentences, where each sentence is either an assumption, or the result of applying a rule of proof to earlier sentences in the sequence.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Each **line of proof** is made up of a **sentence of proof**, together with its **annotation**, its **assumption set**, and the current **line number**.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The assumption set lists the assumptions on which the given sentence of proof depends, which are referenced by the line numbers.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The annotation specifies which rule of proof was applied, and to which earlier lines, to yield the current sentence.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This proof will become clearer when the inference rules and their appropriate annotations are specified – see § Propositional inference rules (Suppes–Lemmon style).
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This section defines the formal syntax for a propositional logic language, contrasting the common ways of doing so with a Gentzen-style way of doing so.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] If $\varphi$ and $\psi$ are formulae, so are $(\varphi \land \psi )$ , $(\varphi \lor \psi )$ , $(\varphi \to \psi )$ , $(\varphi \leftrightarrow \psi )$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] where $\bot$ (falsum) represents a contradiction or absolute falsehood.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Older publications, and publications that do not focus on logical systems like minimal, intuitionistic or Hilbert systems, take negation as a primitive logical connective, meaning it is assumed as a basic operation and not defined in terms of other connectives.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Some authors, such as Bostock, use $\bot$ and $\top$ , and also define $\neg$ as primitives.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] A syntax definition can also be given using § Gentzen's tree notation, by writing well-formed formulas below the inference line and any schematic variables used by those formulas above it.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] A different notational convention sees the language's syntax as a categorial grammar with the single category "formula", denoted by the symbol ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Let the propositional language ${\mathcal {L}}$ be inductively defined as $\Phi ::=p_{1},p_{2},\dots \mid \bot \mid (\Phi \to \Phi )\mid (\Phi \land \Phi )\mid (\Phi \lor \Phi )$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In this table the Greek letters $\varphi ,\psi ,\chi$ are *schemata*, which range over formulas rather than only over atomic propositions.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The name of a rule is given to the right of its formula tree.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] For instance, the first introduction rule is named $\land _{I}$ , which is short for "conjunction introduction".
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] ) is added to the rules for minimal logic, the system defines intuitionistic logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] When all listed natural deduction rules are admitted, the system defines classical logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Later logicians and educators such as Patrick Suppes and E.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] While they introduced graphical changes—such as replacing indentation with vertical bars—the underlying structure of Fitch-style natural deduction remained intact.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] These variations are often referred to as the Suppes–Lemmon format, though they are fundamentally based on Fitch's original notation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The linear presentation used in Fitch- and Suppes–Lemmon-style proofs — with line numbers and vertical alignment/assumption sets — makes subproofs clearly visible.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Fitch (sparingly and cautiously) used **derived rules**.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Suppes–Lemmon went further and added derived rules to the toolbox of natural deduction rules.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Suppes introduced natural deduction using Gentzen-style rules.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] He as well defined negation as implication to falsity: $\neg P\equiv P\to \bot$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In the table below, based on Lemmon (1978) and Allen & Hand (2022), Lemmon's derived rules are highlighted.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] They can be derived from the (non-highlighted) Gentzen rules.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] There are nine primitive rules of proof, which are the rule *assumption*, plus four pairs of introduction and elimination rules for the binary connectives, and the rules of *double negation* and *reductio ad absurdum*, of which only one is needed.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] *Disjunctive Syllogism* can be used as an easier alternative to the proper ∨-elimination, and MTT is a commonly given rule, although it is not primitive.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Recall that an example proof was already given when introducing § Suppes–Lemmon notation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Apply $\neg \neg _{E}$ to get $\varphi$ from $\neg \neg \varphi$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] A theory is said to be consistent if falsehood is not provable (from no assumptions) and is complete if every theorem or its negation is provable using the inference rules of the logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] These are statements about the entire logic, and are usually tied to some notion of a model.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] However, there are local notions of consistency and completeness that are purely syntactic checks on the inference rules, and require no appeals to models.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The first of these is local consistency, also known as local reducibility, which says that any derivation containing an introduction of a connective followed immediately by its elimination can be turned into an equivalent derivation without this detour.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] It is a check on the *strength* of elimination rules: they must not be so strong that they include knowledge not already contained in their premises.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Dually, local completeness says that the elimination rules are strong enough to decompose a connective into the forms suitable for its introduction rule.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] These notions correspond exactly to β-reduction (beta reduction) and η-conversion (eta conversion) in the lambda calculus, using the Curry–Howard isomorphism.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] By local completeness, we see that every derivation can be converted to an equivalent derivation where the principal connective is introduced.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In fact, if the entire derivation obeys this ordering of eliminations followed by introductions, then it is said to be *normal*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In a normal derivation all eliminations happen above introductions.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In most logics, every derivation has an equivalent normal derivation, called a *normal form*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The existence of normal forms is generally hard to prove using natural deduction alone, though such accounts do exist in the literature, most notably by Dag Prawitz in 1961.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] It is much easier to show this indirectly by means of a cut-free sequent calculus presentation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The logic of the earlier section is an example of a *single-sorted* logic, *i.e.*, a logic with a single kind of object: propositions.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Many extensions of this simple framework have been proposed; in this section we will extend it with a second sort of *individuals* or *terms*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] More precisely, we will add a new category, "term", denoted ${\mathcal {T}}$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The first two rules of formation provide a definition of a term that is effectively the same as that defined in term algebra and model theory, although the focus of those fields of study is quite different from natural deduction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The third rule of formation effectively defines an atomic formula, as in first-order logic, and again in model theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In these rules, the notation [*t*/*x*] *A* stands for the substitution of *t* for every (visible) instance of *x* in *A*, avoiding capture.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Although the propositional logic of earlier sections was decidable, adding the quantifiers makes the logic undecidable.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] So far, the quantified extensions are *first-order*: they distinguish propositions from the kinds of objects quantified over.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Higher-order logic takes a different approach and has only a single sort of propositions.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] A discussion of the introduction and elimination forms for higher-order logic is beyond the scope of this article.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] It is possible to be in-between first-order and higher-order logics.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] For example, second-order logic has two kinds of propositions, one kind quantifying over terms, and the second kind quantifying over propositions of the first kind.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The presentation of natural deduction so far has concentrated on the nature of propositions without giving a formal definition of a *proof*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] To formalise the notion of proof, we alter the presentation of hypothetical derivations slightly.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] We label the antecedents with *proof variables* (from some countable set *V* of variables), and decorate the succedent with the actual proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The antecedents or *hypotheses* are separated from the succedent by means of a *turnstile* (⊢).
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This modification sometimes goes under the name of *localised hypotheses*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The following diagram summarises the change.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The collection of hypotheses will be written as Γ when their exact composition is not relevant.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] To make proofs explicit, we move from the proof-less judgment "*A*" to a judgment: "π *is a proof of (A)*", which is written symbolically as "π : *A*".
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Following the standard approach, proofs are specified with their own formation rules for the judgment "π *proof*".
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The simplest possible proof is the use of a labelled hypothesis; in this case the evidence is the label itself.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Let us re-examine some of the connectives with explicit proofs.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] For conjunction, we look at the introduction rule ∧I to discover the form of proofs of conjunction: they must be a pair of proofs of the two conjuncts.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The elimination rules ∧E1 and ∧E2 select either the left or the right conjunct; thus the proofs are a pair of projections—first (**fst**) and second (**snd**).
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] For implication, the introduction form localises or *binds* the hypothesis, written using a λ; this corresponds to the discharged label.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In the rule, "Γ, *u*:*A*" stands for the collection of hypotheses Γ, together with the additional hypothesis *u*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] With proofs available explicitly, one can manipulate and reason about proofs.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The key operation on proofs is the substitution of one proof for an assumption used in another proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This is commonly known as a *substitution theorem*, and can be proved by induction on the depth (or structure) of the second judgment.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] So far the judgment "Γ ⊢ π : *A*" has had a purely logical interpretation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In type theory, the logical view is exchanged for a more computational view of objects.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Propositions in the logical interpretation are now viewed as *types*, and proofs as programs in the lambda calculus.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Thus the interpretation of "π : *A*" is "*the program* π has type *A*".
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The logical connectives are also given a different reading: conjunction is viewed as product (×), implication as the function arrow (→), etc.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The differences are only cosmetic, however.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Type theory has a natural deduction presentation in terms of formation, introduction and elimination rules; in fact, the reader can easily reconstruct what is known as *simple type theory* from the previous sections.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The difference between logic and type theory is primarily a shift of focus from the types (propositions) to the programs (proofs).
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Type theory is chiefly interested in the convertibility or reducibility of programs.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] For every type, there are canonical programs of that type which are irreducible; these are known as *canonical forms* or *values*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] If every program can be reduced to a canonical form, then the type theory is said to be *normalising* (or *weakly normalising*).
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] If the canonical form is unique, then the theory is said to be *strongly normalising*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Normalisability is a rare feature of most non-trivial type theories, which is a big departure from the logical world.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] (Recall that almost every logical derivation has an equivalent normal derivation.) To sketch the reason: in type theories that admit recursive definitions, it is possible to write programs that never reduce to a value; such looping programs can generally be given any type.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] In particular, the looping program has type ⊥, although there is no logical proof of "⊥".
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] For this reason, the *propositions as types; proofs as programs* paradigm only works in one direction, if at all: interpreting a type theory as a logic generally gives an inconsistent logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Like logic, type theory has many extensions and variants, including first-order and higher-order versions.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] One branch, known as dependent type theory, is used in a number of computer-assisted proof systems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Dependent type theory allows quantifiers to range over programs themselves.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] These types are generalisations of the arrow and product types, respectively, as witnessed by their introduction and elimination rules.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Dependent type theory in full generality is very powerful: it is able to express almost any conceivable property of programs directly in the types of the program.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This generality comes at a steep price — either typechecking is undecidable (extensional type theory), or extensional reasoning is more difficult (intensional type theory).
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] For this reason, some dependent type theories do not allow quantification over arbitrary programs, but rather restrict to programs of a given decidable *index domain*, for example integers, strings, or linear programs.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Since dependent type theories allow types to depend on programs, a natural question to ask is whether it is possible for programs to depend on types, or any other combination.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] There are many kinds of answers to such questions.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Various combinations of dependency and polymorphism have been considered in the literature, the most famous being the lambda cube of Henk Barendregt.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The intersection of logic and type theory is a vast and active research area.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] New logics are usually formalised in a general type theoretic setting, known as a logical framework.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Popular modern logical frameworks such as the calculus of constructions and LF are based on higher-order dependent type theory, with various trade-offs in terms of decidability and expressive power.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] These logical frameworks are themselves always specified as natural deduction systems, which is a testament to the versatility of the natural deduction approach.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] For simplicity, the logics presented so far have been intuitionistic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] For any proposition p, the proposition p ∨ ¬p is true.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This statement is not obviously either an introduction or an elimination; indeed, it involves two distinct connectives.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] (XM3 is merely XM2 expressed in terms of E.) This treatment of excluded middle, in addition to being objectionable from a purist's standpoint, introduces additional complications in the definition of normal forms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] A comparatively more satisfactory treatment of classical natural deduction in terms of introduction and elimination rules alone was first proposed by Parigot in 1992 in the form of a classical lambda calculus called λμ.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This structure is essentially lifted directly from classical sequent calculi, but the innovation in λμ was to give a computational meaning to classical natural deduction proofs in terms of a callcc or a throw/catch mechanism seen in LISP and its descendants.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Another important extension was for modal and other logics that need more than just the basic judgment of truth.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] These were first described, for the alethic modal logics S4 and S5, in a natural deduction style by Prawitz in 1965, and have since accumulated a large body of related work.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] If "A" (is true) under no assumption that "B" (is true), then "A valid".
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Note that the premise "*A valid*" has no defining rules; instead, the categorical definition of validity is used in its place.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This mode becomes clearer in the localised form when the hypotheses are explicit.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] We write "Ω;Γ ⊢ *A*" where Γ contains the true hypotheses as before, and Ω contains valid hypotheses.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] On the right there is just a single judgment "*A*"; validity is not needed here since "Ω ⊢ *A valid*" is by definition the same as "Ω;⋅ ⊢ *A*".
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The modal hypotheses have their own version of the hypothesis rule and substitution theorem.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] This framework of separating judgments into distinct collections of hypotheses, also known as *multi-zoned* or *polyadic* contexts, is very powerful and extensible; it has been applied for many different modal logics, and also for linear and other substructural logics, to give a few examples.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] However, relatively few systems of modal logic can be formalised directly in natural deduction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] To give proof-theoretic characterisations of these systems, extensions such as labelling or systems of deep inference.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] The addition of labels to formulae permits much finer control of the conditions under which rules apply, allowing the more flexible techniques of analytic tableaux to be applied, as has been done in the case of labelled deduction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Labels also allow the naming of worlds in Kripke semantics; Simpson (1994) presents an influential technique for converting frame conditions of modal logics in Kripke semantics into inference rules in a natural deduction formalisation of hybrid logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p01] Stouppa (2004) surveys the application of many proof theories, such as Avron and Pottinger's hypersequents and Belnap's display logic to such modal logics as S5 and B.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] The sequent calculus is the chief alternative to natural deduction as a foundation of mathematical logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] In natural deduction the flow of information is bi-directional: elimination rules flow information downwards by deconstruction, and introduction rules flow information upwards by assembly.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] Thus, a natural deduction proof does not have a purely bottom-up or top-down reading, making it unsuitable for automation in proof search.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] To address this fact, Gentzen in 1935 proposed his sequent calculus, though he initially intended it as a technical device for clarifying the consistency of predicate logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] Kleene, in his seminal 1952 book *Introduction to Metamathematics*, gave the first formulation of the sequent calculus in the modern style.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] In the sequent calculus all inference rules have a purely bottom-up reading.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] Inference rules can apply to elements on both sides of the turnstile.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] (To differentiate from natural deduction, this article uses a double arrow ⇒ instead of the right tack ⊢ for sequents.) The introduction rules of natural deduction are viewed as *right rules* in the sequent calculus, and are structurally very similar.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] The elimination rules on the other hand turn into *left rules* in the sequent calculus.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] The proposition *A ∨ B*, which is the succedent of a premise in ∨E, turns into a hypothesis of the conclusion in the left rule ∨L.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] Thus, left rules can be seen as a sort of inverted elimination rule.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] In the sequent calculus, the left and right rules are performed in lock-step until one reaches the *initial sequent*, which corresponds to the meeting point of elimination and introduction rules in natural deduction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] The correspondence between the sequent calculus and natural deduction is a pair of soundness and completeness theorems, which are both provable by means of an inductive argument.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] It is clear by these theorems that the sequent calculus does not change the notion of truth, because the same collection of propositions remain true.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] Thus, one can use the same proof objects as before in sequent calculus derivations.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] As an example, consider the conjunctions.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] The left rule, however, performs some additional substitutions that are not performed in the corresponding elimination rules.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] The kinds of proofs generated in the sequent calculus are therefore rather different from those of natural deduction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] The sequent calculus produces proofs in what is known as the *β-normal η-long* form, which corresponds to a canonical representation of the normal form of the natural deduction proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] If one attempts to describe these proofs using natural deduction itself, one obtains what is called the *intercalation calculus* (first described by John Byrnes), which can be used to formally define the notion of a *normal form* for natural deduction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] The substitution theorem of natural deduction takes the form of a structural rule or structural theorem known as *cut* in the sequent calculus.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] In most well behaved logics, cut is unnecessary as an inference rule, though it remains provable as a meta-theorem; the superfluousness of the cut rule is usually presented as a computational process, known as *cut elimination*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] This has an interesting application for natural deduction; usually it is extremely tedious to prove certain properties directly in natural deduction because of an unbounded number of cases.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] For example, consider showing that a given proposition is *not* provable in natural deduction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] A simple inductive argument fails because of rules like ∨E or E which can introduce arbitrary propositions.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] However, we know that the sequent calculus is complete with respect to natural deduction, so it is enough to show this unprovability in the sequent calculus.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] Now, if cut is not available as an inference rule, then all sequent rules either introduce a connective on the right or the left, so the depth of a sequent derivation is fully bounded by the connectives in the final conclusion.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] Thus, showing unprovability is much easier, because there are only a finite number of cases to consider, and each case is composed entirely of sub-propositions of the conclusion.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] A simple instance of this is the *global consistency* theorem: "⋅ ⊢ ⊥" is not provable.
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] In the sequent calculus version, this is manifestly true because there is no rule that can have "⋅ ⇒ ⊥" as a conclusion!
[src:proof-theory-logic/natural-deduction-p02] Proof theorists often prefer to work on cut-free sequent calculus formulations because of such properties.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] In proof theory, **ordinal analysis** assigns ordinals (often large countable ordinals) to mathematical theories as a measure of their strength.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] If theories have the same proof-theoretic ordinal they are often equiconsistent, and if one theory has a larger proof-theoretic ordinal than another it can often prove the consistency of the second theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] The field of ordinal analysis was formed when Gerhard Gentzen in 1934 used cut elimination to prove, in modern terms, that the **proof-theoretic ordinal** of Peano arithmetic is ε0.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] Ordinal analysis concerns true, effective (recursive) theories that can interpret a sufficient portion of arithmetic to make statements about ordinal notations.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] Equivalently, it is the supremum of all ordinals $\alpha$ such that there exists a recursive relation R on $\omega$ (the set of natural numbers) that well-orders it with ordinal $\alpha$ and such that T proves transfinite induction of arithmetical statements for R .
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] Some theories, such as subsystems of second-order arithmetic (Z2), have no conceptualization or way to make arguments about transfinite ordinals.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] For example, to formalize what it means for a subsystem T of Z2 to "prove $\alpha$ well-ordered", we instead construct an ordinal notation $(A,{\tilde {<}})$ with order type $\alpha$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] T can now work with various transfinite induction principles along $(A,{\tilde {<}})$ , which substitute for reasoning about set-theoretic ordinals.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] However, some pathological notation systems exist that are unexpectedly difficult to work with.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] For example, Rathjen gives a primitive recursive notation system $(\mathbb {N} ,<_{T})$ that is well-founded if and only if PA is consistent,p.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] Including such a notation in the ordinal analysis of PA would result in the false equality ${\mathsf {PTO(PA)}}=\omega$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] Since an ordinal notation must be recursive, the proof-theoretic ordinal of any theory is less than or equal to the Church–Kleene ordinal $\omega _{1}^{\mathrm {CK} }$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] In particular, the proof-theoretic ordinal of an inconsistent theory is equal to $\omega _{1}^{\mathrm {CK} }$ , because an inconsistent theory trivially proves that all ordinal notations are well-founded.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] Friedman's grand conjecture suggests that much "ordinary" mathematics can be proved in weak systems having this as their proof-theoretic ordinal.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] This ordinal is sometimes considered to be the upper limit for "predicative" theories.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] The Kripke–Platek or CZF set theories are weak set theories without axioms for the full powerset given as set of all subsets.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] Instead, they tend to either have axioms of restricted separation and formation of new sets, or they grant existence of certain function spaces (exponentiation) instead of carving them out from bigger relations.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] What is the proof-theoretic ordinal of full second-order arithmetic?
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] Most theories capable of describing the power set of the natural numbers have proof-theoretic ordinals that are so large that no explicit combinatorial description has yet been given.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] This includes $\Pi _{2}^{1}-CA_{0}$ , full second-order arithmetic ( $\Pi _{\infty }^{1}-CA_{0}$ ) and set theories with powersets including ZF and ZFC.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] The strength of intuitionistic ZF (IZF) equals that of ZF.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] In general, a subscript 0 means that the induction scheme is restricted to a single set induction axiom.
[src:proof-theory-logic/ordinal-analysis] A superscript zero indicates that $\in$ -induction is removed (making the theory significantly weaker).
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In mathematical logic, the **Peano axioms** (/piˈɑːnoʊ/; [peˈaːno]), also known as the **Dedekind–Peano axioms** or the **Peano postulates**, are axioms for the natural numbers presented by the 19th-century Italian mathematician Giuseppe Peano.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] These axioms have been used nearly unchanged in a number of metamathematical investigations, including research into fundamental questions of whether number theory is consistent and complete.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The axiomatization of arithmetic provided by Peano axioms is commonly called **Peano arithmetic**.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The importance of formalizing arithmetic was not well appreciated until the work of Hermann Grassmann, who showed in the 1860s that many facts in arithmetic could be derived from more basic facts about the successor operation and induction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In 1881, Charles Sanders Peirce provided an axiomatization of natural-number arithmetic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In 1888, Richard Dedekind proposed another axiomatization of natural-number arithmetic, and in 1889, Peano published a simplified version of them as a collection of axioms in his book *The principles of arithmetic presented by a new method* (Latin: *Arithmetices principia, nova methodo exposita*).
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Peano’s axioms can be divided into groups according to their subject matter.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The first axiom asserts the existence of at least one member of the set of natural numbers.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The next four are general statements about equality; in modern treatments these are often not taken as part of the Peano axioms, but rather as axioms of the "underlying logic".
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The next three axioms are first-order statements about natural numbers expressing the fundamental properties of the successor operation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The ninth, final, axiom is a second-order statement of the principle of mathematical induction over the natural numbers, which makes this formulation close to second-order arithmetic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] A weaker first-order system is obtained by explicitly adding the addition and multiplication operation symbols and replacing the second-order induction axiom with a first-order axiom schema.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The term *Peano arithmetic* is sometimes used for specifically naming this restricted system.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] When Peano formulated his axioms, the language of mathematical logic was in its infancy.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The system of logical notation he created to present the axioms did not prove to be popular, although it was the genesis of the modern notation for set membership (∈, which comes from Peano's ε).
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Peano maintained a clear distinction between mathematical and logical symbols, which was not yet common in mathematics; such a separation had first been introduced in the *Begriffsschrift* by Gottlob Frege, published in 1879.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Peano was unaware of Frege's work and independently recreated his logical apparatus based on the work of Boole and Schröder.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The Peano axioms define the arithmetical properties of *natural numbers*, usually represented as a set **N** or $\mathbb {N} .$ The non-logical symbols for the axioms consist of a constant symbol 0 and a unary function symbol *S*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Peano's original formulation of the axioms used 1 instead of 0 as the "first" natural number, while the axioms in *Formulario mathematico* include zero.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The next four axioms describe the equality relation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Since they are logically valid in first-order logic with equality, they are not considered to be part of "the Peano axioms" in modern treatments.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] For all natural numbers *x* and *y*, if *x* = *y*, then *y* = *x*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] For all *a* and *b*, if *b* is a natural number and *a* = *b*, then *a* is also a natural number.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] That is, the natural numbers are closed under equality.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The remaining axioms define the arithmetical properties of the natural numbers.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The naturals are assumed to be closed under a single-valued "successor" function *S*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] For every natural number *n*, *S*(*n*) = 0 is false.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] That is, there is no natural number whose successor is 0.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Axioms 1, 6, 7, 8 define a unary representation of the intuitive notion of natural numbers: the number 1 can be defined as *S*(0), 2 as *S*(*S*(0)), etc.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] However, considering the notion of natural numbers as being defined by these axioms, axioms 1, 6, 7, 8 do not imply that the successor function generates all the natural numbers different from 0.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The intuitive notion that each natural number can be obtained by applying *successor* sufficiently many times to zero requires an additional axiom, which is sometimes called the *axiom of induction*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In Peano's original formulation, the induction axiom is a second-order axiom.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] It is now common to replace this second-order principle with a weaker first-order induction scheme.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] There are important differences between the second-order and first-order formulations, as discussed in the section § Peano arithmetic as first-order theory below.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] If the second-order induction axiom is used, it is possible to define addition, multiplication, and total (linear) ordering on **N** directly using the axioms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] However, with first-order induction, this is not possible and addition and multiplication are often added as axioms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The respective functions and relations are constructed in set theory or second-order logic, and can be shown to be unique using the Peano axioms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Addition is a function that maps two natural numbers (two elements of **N**) to another one.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] To prove commutativity of addition, first prove $0+b=b$ and $S(a)+b=S(a+b)$ , each by induction on b .
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Using both results, then prove $a+b=b+a$ by induction on b .
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The structure (**N**, +) is a commutative monoid with identity element 0.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] (**N**, +) is also a cancellative magma, and thus embeddable in a group.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The smallest group embedding **N** is the integers.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Similarly, multiplication is a function mapping two natural numbers to another one.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Therefore, by the induction axiom $S(0)$ is the multiplicative left identity of all natural numbers.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Thus, the structure (**N**, +, ·, 1, 0, ≤) is an ordered semiring; because there is no natural number between 0 and 1, it is a discrete ordered semiring.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] This form of the induction axiom, called *strong induction*, is a consequence of the standard formulation, but is often better suited for reasoning about the ≤ order.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] For example, to show that the naturals are well-ordered—every nonempty subset of **N** has a least element—one can reason as follows.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Let a nonempty *X* ⊆ **N** be given and assume *X* has no least element.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Thus, by the strong induction principle, for every *n* ∈ **N**, *n* ∉ *X*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Thus, *X* ∩ **N** = ∅, which contradicts *X* being a nonempty subset of **N**.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] A model of the Peano axioms is a triple (**N**, 0, *S*), where **N** is a (necessarily infinite) set, 0 ∈ **N** and *S*: **N** → **N** satisfies the axioms above.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Dedekind proved in his 1888 book, *The Nature and Meaning of Numbers* (German: *Was sind und was sollen die Zahlen?*, i.e., "What are the numbers and what are they good for?") that any two models of the Peano axioms (including the second-order induction axiom) are isomorphic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] This means that the second-order Peano axioms are categorical.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The Peano axioms can be derived from set theoretic constructions of the natural numbers and axioms of set theory such as ZF.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The set of natural numbers **N** is defined as the intersection of all sets closed under *s* that contain the empty set.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The set **N** together with 0 and the successor function *s* : **N** → **N** satisfies the Peano axioms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Peano arithmetic is equiconsistent with several weak systems of set theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] One such system is ZFC with the axiom of infinity replaced by its negation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Another such system consists of general set theory (extensionality, existence of the empty set, and the axiom of adjunction), augmented by an axiom schema stating that a property that holds for the empty set and holds of an adjunction whenever it holds of the adjunct must hold for all sets.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The Peano axioms can also be understood using category theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Then *C* is said to satisfy the Dedekind–Peano axioms if US1(*C*) has an initial object; this initial object is known as a natural number object in *C*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] This is precisely the recursive definition of 0*X* and *S**X*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] When the Peano axioms were first proposed, Bertrand Russell and others agreed that these axioms implicitly defined what we mean by a "natural number".
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Henri Poincaré was more cautious, saying they only defined natural numbers if they were *consistent*; if there is a proof that starts from just these axioms and derives a contradiction such as 0 = 1, then the axioms are inconsistent, and do not define anything.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In 1900, David Hilbert posed the problem of proving their consistency using only finitistic methods as the second of his twenty-three problems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In 1931, Kurt Gödel proved his second incompleteness theorem, which shows that such a consistency proof cannot be formalized within Peano arithmetic itself, if Peano arithmetic is consistent.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Although it is widely claimed that Gödel's theorem rules out the possibility of a finitistic consistency proof for Peano arithmetic, this depends on exactly what one means by a finitistic proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Gödel himself pointed out the possibility of giving a finitistic consistency proof of Peano arithmetic or stronger systems by using finitistic methods that are not formalizable in Peano arithmetic, and in 1958, Gödel published a method for proving the consistency of arithmetic using type theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In 1936, Gerhard Gentzen gave a proof of the consistency of Peano's axioms, using transfinite induction up to an ordinal called ε0.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Gentzen explained: "The aim of the present paper is to prove the consistency of elementary number theory or, rather, to reduce the question of consistency to certain fundamental principles".
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Gentzen's proof is arguably finitistic, since the transfinite ordinal ε0 can be encoded in terms of finite objects (for example, as a Turing machine describing a suitable order on the integers, or more abstractly as consisting of the finite trees, suitably linearly ordered).
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Whether or not Gentzen's proof meets the requirements Hilbert envisioned is unclear: there is no generally accepted definition of exactly what is meant by a finitistic proof, and Hilbert himself never gave a precise definition.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The vast majority of contemporary mathematicians believe that Peano's axioms are consistent, relying either on intuition or the acceptance of a consistency proof such as Gentzen's proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] A small number of philosophers and mathematicians, some of whom also advocate ultrafinitism, reject Peano's axioms because accepting the axioms amounts to accepting the infinite collection of natural numbers.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In particular, addition (including the successor function) and multiplication are assumed to be total.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] All of the Peano axioms except the ninth axiom (the induction axiom) are statements in first-order logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The arithmetical operations of addition and multiplication and the order relation can also be defined using first-order axioms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The axiom of induction above is second-order, since it quantifies over predicates (equivalently, sets of natural numbers rather than natural numbers).
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] As an alternative one can consider a first-order *axiom schema* of induction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Such a schema includes one axiom per predicate definable in the first-order language of Peano arithmetic, making it weaker than the second-order axiom.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The reason that it is weaker is that the number of predicates in first-order language is countable, whereas the number of sets of natural numbers is uncountable.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Thus, there exist sets that cannot be described in first-order language (in fact, most sets have this property).
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] First-order axiomatizations of Peano arithmetic have another technical limitation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In second-order logic, it is possible to define the addition and multiplication operations from the successor operation, but this cannot be done in the more restrictive setting of first-order logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Therefore, the addition and multiplication operations are directly included in the signature of Peano arithmetic, and axioms are included that relate the three operations to each other.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In addition to this list of numerical axioms, Peano arithmetic contains the induction schema, which consists of a recursively enumerable and even decidable set of axioms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The first-order induction schema includes every instance of the first-order induction axiom; that is, it includes the induction axiom for every formula *φ*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The above axiomatization of Peano arithmetic uses a signature that only has symbols for zero as well as the successor, addition, and multiplications operations.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] There are many other different, but equivalent, axiomatizations.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 3. $\forall x,y,z\ ((x\cdot y)\cdot z=x\cdot (y\cdot z))$ , i.e., multiplication is associative.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 4. $\forall x,y\ (x\cdot y=y\cdot x)$ , i.e., multiplication is commutative.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 5. $\forall x,y,z\ (x\cdot (y+z)=(x\cdot y)+(x\cdot z))$ , i.e., multiplication distributes over addition.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 6. $\forall x\ (x+0=x\land x\cdot 0=0)$ , i.e., zero is an identity for addition, and an absorbing element for multiplication (actually superfluous).
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 7. $\forall x\ (x\cdot 1=x)$ , i.e., one is an identity for multiplication.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 8. $\forall x,y,z\ (x<y\land y<z\Rightarrow x<z)$ , i.e., the '<' operator is transitive.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 10. $\forall x,y\ (x<y\lor x=y\lor y<x)$ , i.e., the ordering satisfies trichotomy.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 11. $\forall x,y,z\ (x<y\Rightarrow x+z<y+z)$ , i.e. the ordering is preserved under addition of the same element.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 12. $\forall x,y,z\ (0<z\land x<y\Rightarrow x\cdot z<y\cdot z)$ , i.e. the ordering is preserved under multiplication by the same positive element.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 13. $\forall x,y\ (x<y\Rightarrow \exists z\ (x+z=y))$ , i.e. given any two distinct elements, the larger is the smaller plus another element.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 14. $0<1\land \forall x\ (x>0\Rightarrow x\geq 1)$ , i.e. zero and one are distinct and there is no element between them.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In other words, 0 is covered by 1, which suggests that these numbers are discrete.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] 15. $\forall x\ (x\geq 0)$ , i.e. zero is the minimum element.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The theory defined by these axioms is known as **PA−**.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] It is also incomplete and one of its important properties is that any structure M satisfying this theory has an initial segment (ordered by $\leq$ ) isomorphic to $\mathbb {N}$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Elements in that segment are called **standard** elements, while other elements are called **nonstandard** elements.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Finally, Peano arithmetic **PA** is obtained by adding the first-order induction schema.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] According to Gödel's incompleteness theorems, the theory of **PA** (if consistent) is incomplete.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Consequently, there are sentences of first-order logic (FOL) that are true in the standard model of **PA** but are not a consequence of the FOL axiomatization.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Essential incompleteness already arises for theories with weaker axioms, such as Robinson arithmetic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Closely related to the above incompleteness result (via Gödel's completeness theorem for FOL) it follows that there is no algorithm for deciding whether a given FOL sentence is a consequence of a first-order axiomatization of Peano arithmetic or not.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Hence, **PA** is an example of an undecidable theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Undecidability arises already for the existential sentences of **PA**, due to the negative answer to Hilbert's tenth problem, whose proof implies that all computably enumerable sets are diophantine sets, and thus definable by existentially quantified formulas (with free variables) of **PA**.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Formulas of **PA** with higher quantifier rank (more quantifier alternations) than existential formulas are more expressive, and define sets in the higher levels of the arithmetical hierarchy.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Although the usual natural numbers satisfy the axioms of PA, there are other models as well (called "non-standard models"); the compactness theorem implies that the existence of nonstandard elements cannot be excluded in first-order logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The upward Löwenheim–Skolem theorem shows that there are nonstandard models of PA of all infinite cardinalities.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] This is not the case for the original (second-order) Peano axioms, which have only one model, up to isomorphism.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] This illustrates one way the first-order system PA is weaker than the second-order Peano axioms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] In the standard model of set theory, this smallest model of PA is the standard model of PA; however, in a nonstandard model of set theory, it may be a nonstandard model of PA.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] This situation cannot be avoided with any first-order formalization of set theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] It is natural to ask whether a countable nonstandard model can be explicitly constructed.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The answer is affirmative as Skolem in 1933 provided an explicit construction of such a nonstandard model.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] On the other hand, Tennenbaum's theorem, proved in 1959, shows that there is no countable nonstandard model of PA in which either the addition or multiplication operation is computable.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] This result shows it is difficult to be completely explicit in describing the addition and multiplication operations of a countable nonstandard model of PA.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] There is only one possible order type of a countable nonstandard model.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] A **cut** in a nonstandard model *M* is a nonempty subset *C* of *M* so that *C* is downward closed (*x* < *y* and *y* ∈ *C* ⇒ *x* ∈ *C*) and *C* is closed under successor.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] A **proper cut** is a cut that is a proper subset of *M*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] Each nonstandard model has many proper cuts, including one that corresponds to the standard natural numbers.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] However, the induction scheme in Peano arithmetic prevents any proper cut from being definable.
[src:proof-theory-logic/peano-axioms] The overspill lemma, first proved by Abraham Robinson, formalizes this fact.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Some of the major areas of proof theory include structural proof theory, ordinal analysis, provability logic, proof-theoretic semantics, reverse mathematics, proof mining, automated theorem proving, and proof complexity.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Much research also focuses on applications in computer science, linguistics, and philosophy.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The failure of the program was induced by Kurt Gödel's incompleteness theorems, which showed that any ω-consistent theory that is sufficiently strong to express certain simple arithmetic truths, cannot prove its own consistency, which on Gödel's formulation is a $\Pi _{1}^{0}$ sentence.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] However, modified versions of Hilbert's program emerged and research has been carried out on related topics.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] In parallel to the rise and fall of Hilbert's program, the foundations of structural proof theory were being founded.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Jan Łukasiewicz suggested in 1926 that one could improve on Hilbert systems as a basis for the axiomatic presentation of logic if one allowed the drawing of conclusions from assumptions in the inference rules of the logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Together, the presentation of natural deduction and the sequent calculus introduced the fundamental idea of analytic proof to proof theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Structural proof theory is the subdiscipline of proof theory that studies the specifics of proof calculi.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Each of these can give a complete and axiomatic formalization of propositional or predicate logic of either the classical or intuitionistic flavour, almost any modal logic, and many substructural logics, such as relevance logic or linear logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Indeed, it is unusual to find a logic that resists being represented in one of these calculi.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Proof theorists are typically interested in proof calculi that have certain good properties.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] One good family of properties is **analyticity**.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The notion of an analytic proof was introduced by Gentzen for the sequent calculus, where he proved that the sequent calculus of classical and intuitionistic logics are cut-free.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] One notion of analyticity is the **cut-elimination property**: a proof calculus has the cut-elimination property if it has the cut rule, but any provable sequent is provable without the cut rule.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Gentzen's midsequent theorem, the Craig interpolation theorem, and Herbrand's theorem follow as corollaries of the cut-elimination property.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Another notion of analyticity is the **subformula property**.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] A proof has the subformula property if every of its formula is a subformula of its endsequent.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] A proof calculus has the subformula property if all its provable sequents can be proved by a proof with the subformula property.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] In most proof calculi, the subformula property follows from the cut-elimination property, though not necessarily *vice versa*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] A proof calculus with the subformula property is consistent, since if the empty sequent were derivable it would have to be a subformula of some premise, which it is not.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Gentzen's natural deduction calculus also supports a notion of analytic proof, as shown by Dag Prawitz.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The definition is slightly more complex: we say the analytic proofs are the normal forms, which are related to the notion of normal form in term rewriting.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] More exotic proof calculi such as Jean-Yves Girard's proof nets also support a notion of analytic proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] A particular family of analytic proofs arising in reductive logic are **focused** proofs which characterise a large family of goal-directed proof-search procedures.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The ability to transform a proof system into a focused form is a good indication of its syntactic quality, in a manner similar to how admissibility of cut shows that a proof system is syntactically consistent.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] In a natural deduction system, each logical connectives has a pair of rules: rules for introduction, and rules for elimination.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The pair of rules is said to be in harmony if in any proof, maximal formulas can be eliminated by normalizing the proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] A maximal formula is a formula that is introduced, then eliminated later.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The idea is that such maximal formulas behave similarly to lemmas, and while they can make the proof easier to write and shorter, are not strictly necessary.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] A normalized proof ought to only introduce logical connectives, and never eliminate them.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Certain inference rules are **local**, which is a desired property.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] In this sense, the rule is *not local*, since in order to apply the rule, one must check an unbounded number of formulas.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Structural proof theory is connected to type theory by means of the Curry–Howard correspondence, which observes a structural analogy between the process of normalisation in the natural deduction calculus and beta reduction in the typed lambda calculus.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] This provides the foundation for the intuitionistic type theory developed by Per Martin-Löf, and is often extended to a three way correspondence, the third leg of which are the cartesian closed categories.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Other research topics in structural theory include analytic tableau, which apply the central idea of analytic proof from structural proof theory to provide decision procedures and semi-decision procedures for a wide range of logics, and the proof theory of substructural logics.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Ordinal analysis is a powerful technique for providing combinatorial consistency proofs for subsystems of arithmetic, analysis, and set theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Gödel's second incompleteness theorem is often interpreted as demonstrating that finitistic consistency proofs are impossible for theories of sufficient strength.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Ordinal analysis allows one to measure precisely the infinitary content of the consistency of theories.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] For a consistent recursively axiomatized theory T, one can prove in finitistic arithmetic that the well-foundedness of a certain transfinite ordinal implies the consistency of T.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Gödel's second incompleteness theorem implies that the well-foundedness of such an ordinal cannot be proved in the theory T.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Consequences of ordinal analysis include (1) consistency of subsystems of classical second order arithmetic and set theory relative to constructive theories, (2) combinatorial independence results, and (3) classifications of provably total recursive functions and provably well-founded ordinals.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Ordinal analysis was originated by Gentzen, who proved the consistency of Peano Arithmetic using transfinite induction up to ordinal ε0.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Ordinal analysis has been extended to many fragments of first and second order arithmetic and set theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] One major challenge has been the ordinal analysis of impredicative theories.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The first breakthrough in this direction was Takeuti's proof of the consistency of Π1 1-CA0 using the method of ordinal diagrams.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Some of the basic results concerning the incompleteness of Peano Arithmetic and related theories have analogues in provability logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] For example, it is a theorem in GL that if a contradiction is not provable then it is not provable that a contradiction is not provable (Gödel's second incompleteness theorem).
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] There are also modal analogues of the fixed-point theorem.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Robert Solovay proved that the modal logic GL is complete with respect to Peano Arithmetic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] That is, the propositional theory of provability in Peano Arithmetic is completely represented by the modal logic GL.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] This straightforwardly implies that propositional reasoning about provability in Peano Arithmetic is complete and decidable.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Some very recent research has involved applications of graded provability algebras to the ordinal analysis of arithmetical theories.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Reverse mathematics is a program in mathematical logic that seeks to determine which axioms are required to prove theorems of mathematics.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The field was founded by Harvey Friedman.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Its defining method can be described as "going backwards from the theorems to the axioms", in contrast to the ordinary mathematical practice of deriving theorems from axioms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The reverse mathematics program was foreshadowed by results in set theory such as the classical theorem that the axiom of choice and Zorn's lemma are equivalent over ZF set theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The goal of reverse mathematics, however, is to study possible axioms of ordinary theorems of mathematics rather than possible axioms for set theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] In reverse mathematics, one starts with a framework language and a base theory—a core axiom system—that is too weak to prove most of the theorems one might be interested in, but still powerful enough to develop the definitions necessary to state these theorems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] For example, to study the theorem "Every bounded sequence of real numbers has a supremum" it is necessary to use a base system that can speak of real numbers and sequences of real numbers.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] For each theorem that can be stated in the base system but is not provable in the base system, the goal is to determine the particular axiom system (stronger than the base system) that is necessary to prove that theorem.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] To show that a system *S* is required to prove a theorem *T*, two proofs are required.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The first proof shows *T* is provable from *S*; this is an ordinary mathematical proof along with a justification that it can be carried out in the system *S*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The second proof, known as a **reversal**, shows that *T* itself implies *S*; this proof is carried out in the base system.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The reversal establishes that no axiom system *S′* that extends the base system can be weaker than *S* while still proving *T*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] One striking phenomenon in reverse mathematics is the robustness of the *Big Five* axiom systems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] In order of increasing strength, these systems are named by the initialisms RCA0, WKL0, ACA0, ATR0, and Π1 1-CA0.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Nearly every theorem of ordinary mathematics that has been reverse mathematically analyzed has been proven equivalent to one of these five systems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Much recent research has focused on combinatorial principles that do not fit neatly into this framework, like RT2 2 (Ramsey's theorem for pairs).
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Research in reverse mathematics often incorporates methods and techniques from recursion theory as well as proof theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Functional interpretations are interpretations of non-constructive theories in functional ones.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Functional interpretations usually proceed in two stages.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] First, one "reduces" a classical theory C to an intuitionistic one I.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] That is, one provides a constructive mapping that translates the theorems of C to the theorems of I.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Second, one reduces the intuitionistic theory I to a quantifier free theory of functionals F.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] These interpretations contribute to a form of Hilbert's program, since they prove the consistency of classical theories relative to constructive ones.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Successful functional interpretations have yielded reductions of infinitary theories to finitary theories and impredicative theories to predicative ones.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Functional interpretations also provide a way to extract constructive information from proofs in the reduced theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] As a direct consequence of the interpretation one usually obtains the result that any recursive function whose totality can be proven either in I or in C is represented by a term of F.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] If one can provide an additional interpretation of F in I, which is sometimes possible, this characterization is in fact usually shown to be exact.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] It often turns out that the terms of F coincide with a natural class of functions, such as the primitive recursive or polynomial-time computable functions.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Functional interpretations have also been used to provide ordinal analyses of theories and classify their provably recursive functions.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The study of functional interpretations began with Kurt Gödel's interpretation of intuitionistic arithmetic in a quantifier-free theory of functionals of finite type.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] This interpretation is commonly known as the Dialectica interpretation.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Together with the double-negation interpretation of classical logic in intuitionistic logic, it provides a reduction of classical arithmetic to intuitionistic arithmetic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] The *informal* proofs of everyday mathematical practice are unlike the *formal* proofs of proof theory.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] They are rather like high-level sketches that would allow an expert to reconstruct a formal proof at least in principle, given enough time and patience.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] For most mathematicians, writing a fully formal proof is too pedantic and long-winded to be in common use.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Formal proofs are constructed with the help of computers in interactive theorem proving.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Significantly, these proofs can be checked automatically, also by computer.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] Checking formal proofs is usually simple, whereas *finding* proofs (automated theorem proving) is generally hard.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] An informal proof in the mathematics literature, by contrast, requires weeks of peer review to be checked, and may still contain errors.
[src:proof-theory-logic/proof-theory] In linguistics, type-logical grammar, categorial grammar and Montague grammar apply formalisms based on structural proof theory to give a formal natural language semantics.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In mathematical logic, **sequent calculus** is a style of formal logical argumentation in which every line of a proof is a conditional tautology (called a sequent by Gerhard Gentzen) instead of an unconditional tautology.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] More subtle distinctions may exist; for example, propositions may implicitly depend upon non-logical axioms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In that case, sequents signify conditional theorems of a first-order theory rather than conditional tautologies.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Sequent calculus is one of several extant styles of proof calculus for expressing line-by-line logical arguments.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In other words, natural deduction and sequent calculus systems are particular distinct kinds of Gentzen-style systems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Hilbert-style systems typically have a very small number of inference rules, relying more on sets of axioms.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Gentzen-style systems typically have very few axioms, if any, relying more on sets of rules.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Gentzen-style systems have significant practical and theoretical advantages compared to Hilbert-style systems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] For example, both natural deduction and sequent calculus systems facilitate the elimination and introduction of universal and existential quantifiers so that unquantified logical expressions can be manipulated according to the much simpler rules of propositional calculus.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In a typical argument, quantifiers are eliminated, then propositional calculus is applied to unquantified expressions (which typically contain free variables), and then the quantifiers are reintroduced.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This very much parallels the way in which mathematical proofs are carried out in practice by mathematicians.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Predicate calculus proofs are generally much easier to discover with this approach, and are often shorter.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Natural deduction systems are more suited to practical theorem-proving.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Sequent calculus systems are more suited to theoretical analysis.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In proof theory and mathematical logic, sequent calculus is a family of formal systems sharing a certain style of inference and certain formal properties.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The first sequent calculi systems, **LK** and **LJ**, were introduced in 1934/1935 by Gerhard Gentzen as a tool for studying natural deduction in first-order logic (in classical and intuitionistic versions, respectively).
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Gentzen's so-called "Main Theorem" (*Hauptsatz*) about LK and LJ was the cut-elimination theorem, a result with far-reaching meta-theoretic consequences, including consistency.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Gentzen further demonstrated the power and flexibility of this technique a few years later, applying a cut-elimination argument to give a (transfinite) proof of the consistency of Peano arithmetic, in surprising response to Gödel's incompleteness theorems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Since this early work, sequent calculi, also called **Gentzen systems**, and the general concepts relating to them, have been widely applied in the fields of proof theory, mathematical logic, and automated deduction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] One way to classify different styles of deduction systems is to look at the form of *judgments* in the system, *i.e.*, which things may appear as the conclusion of a (sub)proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] where B is any formula of first-order logic (or whatever logic the deduction system applies to, *e.g.*, propositional calculus or a higher-order logic or a modal logic).
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The theorems are those formulas that appear as the concluding judgment in a valid proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] A Hilbert-style system needs no distinction between formulas and judgments; we make one here solely for comparison with the cases that follow.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The price paid for the simple syntax of a Hilbert-style system is that complete formal proofs tend to get extremely long.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Concrete arguments about proofs in such a system almost always appeal to the deduction theorem.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This leads to the idea of including the deduction theorem as a formal rule in the system, which happens in natural deduction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] where the $A_{i}$ 's and B are again formulas and $n\geq 0$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In other words, a judgment consists of a *list* (possibly empty) of formulas on the left-hand side of a turnstile symbol " $\vdash$ ", with a single formula on the right-hand side, (though permutations of the $A_{i}$ 's are often immaterial).
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The theorems are those formulae B such that $\vdash B$ (with an empty left-hand side) is the conclusion of a valid proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The standard semantics of a judgment in natural deduction is that it asserts that whenever $A_{1}$ , $A_{2}$ , etc., are all true, B will also be true.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] are equivalent in the strong sense that a proof of either one may be extended to a proof of the other.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The formulas on left-hand side of the turnstile are called the *antecedent*, and the formulas on right-hand side are called the *succedent* or *consequent*; together they are called *cedents* or *sequent formulas*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Again, $A_{i}$ and $B_{i}$ are formulas, and n and k are nonnegative integers, that is, the left-hand-side or the right-hand-side (or neither or both) may be empty.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] As in natural deduction, theorems are those B where $\vdash B$ is the conclusion of a valid proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The standard semantics of a sequent is an assertion that whenever *every* $A_{i}$ is true, *at least one* $B_{i}$ will also be true.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Thus the empty sequent, having both cedents empty, is false.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] One way to express this is that a comma to the left of the turnstile should be thought of as an "and", and a comma to the right of the turnstile should be thought of as an (inclusive) "or".
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] are equivalent in the strong sense that a proof of either sequent may be extended to a proof of the other sequent.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] At first sight, this extension of the judgment form may appear to be a strange complication—it is not motivated by an obvious shortcoming of natural deduction, and it is initially confusing that the comma seems to mean entirely different things on the two sides of the turnstile.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] (it cannot be the case that all of the As are true and all of the Bs are false).
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In these formulations, the only difference between formulas on either side of the turnstile is that one side is negated.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Thus, swapping left for right in a sequent corresponds to negating all of the constituent formulas.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Many logicians feel that this symmetric presentation offers a deeper insight in the structure of the logic than other styles of proof system, where the classical duality of negation is not as apparent in the rules.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Gentzen asserted a sharp distinction between his single-output natural deduction systems (NK and NJ) and his multiple-output sequent calculus systems (LK and LJ).
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] He wrote that the intuitionistic natural deduction system NJ was somewhat ugly.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] He said that the special role of the excluded middle in the classical natural deduction system NK is removed in the classical sequent calculus system LK.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] He said that the sequent calculus LJ gave more symmetry than natural deduction NJ in the case of intuitionistic logic, as also in the case of classical logic (LK versus NK).
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Then he said that in addition to these reasons, the sequent calculus with multiple succedent formulas is intended particularly for his principal theorem ("Hauptsatz").
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The word "sequent" is taken from the word "Sequenz" in Gentzen's 1934 paper.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Gentzen used two-letter capitals to stand for various proof systems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In his 1935 paper, he stated that in **LK**, the **L** stood for "logische" (logical) and the **K** stood for "klassische Pradikatenlogik" ("classical predicative logic").
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The **J** in **LJ** stood for "intuitionistische Pradikatenlogik" ("intuitionistic predicative logic").
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Similarly, the **N** in **NK** and **NJ** stood for "natürlichen Schließens" ("natural deduction").
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] It is unclear how he came to use **J** to stand for "intuitionistische", but presumably to typographically distinguish it from the numeral 1 and the Roman numeral I.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In other places, Gentzen used **LI** and **NI** instead of **LJ** and **NJ**.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Sequent calculus can be seen as a tool for proving formulas in propositional logic, similar to the method of analytic tableaux.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] It gives a series of steps that allows one to reduce the problem of proving a logical formula to simpler and simpler formulas until one arrives at trivial ones.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Now, instead of proving this from the axioms, it is enough to assume the premise of the implication and then try to prove its conclusion.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This is equivalent to proving the conclusion in both cases of the disjunction on the first argument on the left.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This process can always be continued until there are only atomic formulas in each side.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The process can be graphically described by a rooted tree, as depicted on the right.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The root of the tree is the formula we wish to prove; the leaves consist of atomic formulas only.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The tree is known as a **reduction tree**.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The items to the left of the turnstile are understood to be connected by conjunction, and those to the right by disjunction.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Therefore, when both consist only of atomic symbols, the sequent is accepted axiomatically (and always true) if and only if at least one of the symbols on the right also appears on the left.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Following are the rules by which one proceeds along the tree.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Whenever one sequent is split into two, the tree vertex has two child vertices, and the tree is branched.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Additionally, one may freely change the order of the arguments in each side; Γ and Δ stand for possible additional arguments.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The usual term for the horizontal line used in Gentzen-style layouts for natural deduction is **inference line**.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Starting with any formula in propositional logic, by a series of steps, the right side of the turnstile can be processed until it includes only atomic symbols.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Then, the same is done for the left side.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Since every logical operator appears in one of the rules above, and is removed by the rule, the process terminates when no logical operators remain: The formula has been *decomposed*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Thus, the sequents in the leaves of the trees include only atomic symbols, which are either provable by the axiom or not, according to whether one of the symbols on the right also appears on the left.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] It is easy to see that the steps in the tree preserve the semantic truth value of the formulas implied by them, with conjunction understood between the tree's different branches whenever there is a split.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] It is also obvious that an axiom is provable if and only if it is true for every assignment of truth values to the atomic symbols.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Thus this system is sound and complete for classical propositional logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Sequent calculus is related to other axiomatizations of classical propositional calculus, such as Frege's propositional calculus or Jan Łukasiewicz's axiomatization (itself a part of the standard Hilbert system): Every formula that can be proven in these has a reduction tree.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This can be shown as follows: Every proof in propositional calculus uses only axioms and the inference rules.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Each use of an axiom scheme yields a true logical formula, and can thus be proven in sequent calculus; examples for these are shown below.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The only inference rule in the systems mentioned above is modus ponens, which is implemented by the cut rule.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This section introduces the rules of the sequent calculus **LK** (standing for Logistische Kalkül) as introduced by Gentzen in 1934.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] A (formal) proof in this calculus is a finite sequence of sequents, where each of the sequents is derivable from sequents appearing earlier in the sequence by using one of the rules below.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Note that, contrary to the rules for proceeding along the reduction tree presented above, the following rules are for moving in the opposite directions, from axioms to theorems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Thus they are exact mirror-images of the rules above, except that here symmetry is not implicitly assumed, and rules regarding quantification are added.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In the table below, $A\setminus B$ denotes the relative complement of B in A .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The above rules can be divided into two major groups: *logical* and *structural* ones.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Each of the logical rules introduces a new logical formula either on the left or on the right of the turnstile $\vdash$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In contrast, the structural rules operate on the structure of the sequents, ignoring the exact shape of the formulas.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The two exceptions to this general scheme are the axiom of identity (I) and the rule of (Cut).
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Although stated in a formal way, the above rules allow for a very intuitive reading in terms of classical logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Consider, for example, the rule $({\land }L_{1})$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] It says that, whenever one can prove that $\Delta$ can be concluded from some sequence of formulas that contain A , then one can also conclude $\Delta$ from the (stronger) assumption that $A\land B$ holds.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Likewise, the rule $({\neg }R)$ states that, if $\Gamma$ and A suffice to conclude $\Delta$ , then from $\Gamma$ alone one can either still conclude $\Delta$ or that A must be false, i.e. ${\neg }A$ holds.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] All the rules can be interpreted in this way.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] For an intuition about the quantifier rules, consider the rule $({\forall }R)$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Of course concluding that $\forall {x}A$ holds just from the fact that $A[y/x]$ is true is not in general possible.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] If, however, the variable *y* is not mentioned elsewhere (i.e. it can still be chosen freely, without influencing the other formulas), then one may assume, that $A[y/x]$ holds for any value of *y*.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The other rules should then be pretty straightforward.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Instead of viewing the rules as descriptions for legal derivations in predicate logic, one may also consider them as instructions for the construction of a proof for a given statement.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In this case the rules can be read bottom-up; for example, $({\land }R)$ says that, to prove that $A\land B$ follows from the assumptions $\Gamma$ and $\Sigma$ , it suffices to prove that A can be concluded from $\Gamma$ and B can be concluded from $\Sigma$ , respectively.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Note that, given some antecedent, it is not clear how this is to be split into $\Gamma$ and $\Sigma$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] However, there are only finitely many possibilities to be checked since the antecedent by assumption is finite.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This also illustrates how proof theory can be viewed as operating on proofs in a combinatorial fashion: given proofs for both A and B , one can construct a proof for $A\land B$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] When looking for some proof, most of the rules offer more or less direct recipes of how to do this.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The rule of cut is different: it states that, when a formula A can be concluded and this formula may also serve as a premise for concluding other statements, then the formula A can be "cut out" and the respective derivations are joined.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] When constructing a proof bottom-up, this creates the problem of guessing A (since it does not appear at all below).
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The cut-elimination theorem is thus crucial to the applications of sequent calculus in automated deduction: it states that all uses of the cut rule can be eliminated from a proof, implying that any provable sequent can be given a *cut-free* proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The second rule that is somewhat special is the axiom of identity (I).
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The intuitive reading of this is obvious: every formula proves itself.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Like the cut rule, the axiom of identity is somewhat redundant: the completeness of atomic initial sequents states that the rule can be restricted to atomic formulas without any loss of provability.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Observe that, if we ignore the non-standard connective \, all rules have mirror companions, except the ones for implication.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This reflects the fact that the usual language of first-order logic does not include the "is not implied by" connective $\not \leftarrow$ that would be the De Morgan dual of implication.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Adding such a connective with its natural rules makes the calculus completely left–right symmetric.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Here is the derivation of " $\vdash A\lor \lnot A$ ", known as the *Law of excluded middle* (*tertium non datur* in Latin).
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Next is the proof of a simple fact involving quantifiers.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Note that the converse is not true, and its falsity can be seen when attempting to derive it bottom-up, because an existing free variable cannot be used in substitution in the rules $(\forall R)$ and $(\exists L)$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] For something more interesting we shall prove ${\left(\left(A\rightarrow \left(B\lor C\right)\right)\rightarrow \left(\left(\left(B\rightarrow \lnot A\right)\land \lnot C\right)\rightarrow \lnot A\right)\right)}$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] It is straightforward to find the derivation, which exemplifies the usefulness of LK in automated proving.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] These derivations also emphasize the strictly formal structure of the sequent calculus.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] For example, the logical rules as defined above always act on a formula immediately adjacent to the turnstile, such that the permutation rules are necessary.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Note, however, that this is in part an artifact of the presentation, in the original style of Gentzen.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] A common simplification involves the use of multisets of formulas in the interpretation of the sequent, rather than sequences, eliminating the need for an explicit permutation rule.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This corresponds to shifting commutativity of assumptions and derivations outside the sequent calculus, whereas LK embeds it within the system itself.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] For certain formulations (i.e. variants) of the sequent calculus, a proof in such a calculus is isomorphic to an upside-down, closed analytic tableau.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The structural rules deserve some additional discussion.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Weakening (W) allows the addition of arbitrary elements to a sequence.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Contraction (C) and Permutation (P) assure that neither the order (P) nor the multiplicity of occurrences (C) of elements of the sequences matters.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Thus, one could instead of sequences also consider sets.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The extra effort of using sequences, however, is justified since part or all of the structural rules may be omitted.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Doing so, one obtains the so-called substructural logics.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This system of rules can be shown to be both sound and complete with respect to first-order logic, i.e. a statement A follows semantically from a set of premises $\Gamma$ $(\Gamma \vDash A)$ if and only if the sequent $\Gamma \vdash A$ can be derived by the above rules.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In the sequent calculus, the rule of cut is admissible.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This result is also referred to as Gentzen's *Hauptsatz* ("Main Theorem").
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] There is some freedom of choice regarding the technical details of how sequents and structural rules are formalized without changing what sequents the system derives.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] First of all, as mentioned above, the sequents can be viewed to consist of sets or multisets.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In this case, the rules for permuting and (when using sets) contracting formulas are unnecessary.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] The rule of weakening becomes admissible if the axiom (I) is changed to derive any sequent of the form $\Gamma ,A\vdash A,\Delta$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Any weakening that appears in a derivation can then be moved to the beginning of the proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This may be a convenient change when constructing proofs bottom-up.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Contraction and weakening make this version of the rule interderivable with the version above, although in their absence, as in linear logic, these rules define different connectives.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] With $\bot$ , negation can be subsumed as a special case of implication, via the definition $(\neg A)\iff (A\to \bot )$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Alternatively, one may restrict or forbid the use of some of the structural rules.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This yields a variety of substructural logic systems.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] They are generally weaker than LK (*i.e.*, they have fewer theorems), and thus not complete with respect to the standard semantics of first-order logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] However, they have other interesting properties that have led to applications in theoretical computer science and artificial intelligence.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] Surprisingly, some small changes in the rules of LK suffice to turn it into a proof system for intuitionistic logic.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] To this end, one has to restrict to sequents with at most one formula on the right-hand side, and modify the rules to maintain this invariant.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] It is sound and complete with respect to intuitionistic logic and admits a similar cut-elimination proof.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] This can be used in proving disjunction and existence properties.
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] In fact, the only rules in LK that need to be restricted to single-formula consequents are $({\to }R)$ , $(\neg R)$ (which can be seen as a special case of ${\to }R$ , as described above) and $({\forall }R)$ .
[src:proof-theory-logic/sequent-calculus] These two rules are *not* intuitionistically valid.
